article.description: Yolanda Griffith and Nicole Powell each scored 18 points and Sacramento held off a late Sparks rally to win 75-72 in Los Angeles on Wednesday night in Game 1.
article.headline: Sacramento withstands Sparks rally, takes opener
article.linkText: Sacramento withstands Sparks rally to win in L.A.
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Sacramento got careless with the ball and it
nearly cost the Monarchs.

Yolanda Griffith and Nicole Powell each scored 18 points and
Sacramento held off a late rally to beat the Los Angeles Sparks
75-72 on Wednesday night in their WNBA playoff opener.

"It was a dogfight from beginning to end," said Griffith, who
played with a cold. "We knew L.A. wasn't going to give up. We kept
our composure, but we can't turn the ball over like that. I hope we
learn from this."

The Monarchs blew most of a 16-point lead over the final 8
minutes and committed 19 turnovers in the game, but hung on when
Lisa Leslie missed two layups in the final seconds.

"We encouraged them to come back instead of getting them down
and holding them down like you would like," Monarchs coach John
Whisenant said. "I'd like to have the last 3 or 4 minutes over. We
got a little tight with the ball, and I was encouraging them to
attack."

Instead, the Sparks were the aggressors.

Trailing 75-70, Nikki Teasley scored on a fast break and was
fouled by Powell with 2.8 seconds left. She deliberately missed the
free throw, Leslie grabbed the rebound and put up a layup that
missed as time expired.

"The ball went in and out. That's the way the game bounces,"
Leslie said.

Los Angeles outscored Sacramento 20-11 over the final 8 minutes,
getting within three on a 3-pointer by Chamique Holdsclaw with 58
seconds left. Powell hit two free throws for Sacramento, then
Leslie missed a layup and Teasley's 3-pointer was off the mark,
too.

"Sacramento played great and really rebounded the ball,"
Holdsclaw said. "We didn't box out as well as we could have."

Holdsclaw led the Sparks with 24 points and Leslie added 12.

The Monarchs continued their domination of the Sparks, who must
win Game 2 at Sacramento on Friday night to avoid being eliminated
in the first round for the second consecutive year.

"This game really got everybody's attention," Holdsclaw said.

The top-seeded Monarchs won three of four games against the
fourth-seeded Sparks during the regular season, and they never
trailed Wednesday.

Ticha Penicheiro had nine assists and Rebekkah Brunson grabbed
11 rebounds as the Monarchs controlled the boards, 29-15, like they
did in their three regular-season wins.

"They did a good job of keeping us off the boards," Leslie
said. "We felt we needed this game. We did all you can ask. We
played hard and we still believe in ourselves."

Sacramento shot 63 percent from the field, getting off to a fast
start by scoring the game's first nine points.

"We just didn't make the right decisions," Sparks coach Joe
Bryant said. "We missed two or three point-blank shots. Could we
have won the game? No doubt about it. They can be beaten."

The Monarchs didn't need All-Star forward DeMya Walker, who will
miss the series with a sprained right knee.

Sacramento led by 13 points at halftime and extended its lead to
54-38 on two free throws by Griffith when Leslie picked up her
third foul with 16:12 remaining.

The Sparks cut their deficit to single digits on Leslie's
fastbreak layin that left them trailing by nine. Raffaella
Masciadri's jumper pulled them to 71-64 with 2:54 left.

The Sparks are close to ending a disappointing season that has
been plagued by injuries and a coaching change earlier in August,
when Bryant replaced Henry Bibby.

"I think we are getting better, but I don't know if we have
enough time," Leslie said.

A year ago, the Sparks were the West's No. 1 seed and owned the
league's best record, but lost in the first round to Sacramento.
